ert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Heribert","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Herbert FitzPeter, Lord of Llanlowell was born in 1255, in Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Peter FitzReynold ,Knight, was 28 and his mother, Alice Broadspear, was 27. He had at least 1 son with Margaret Walsh. He died on 18 November 1322, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1255–18 November 1322":"1255–18. november 1322","1255–1322":"1255–1322","1255–Female":"1255–Surnud","1274–1345":"1274–1345","1228–1322":"1228–1322","1228–1315":"1228–1315","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1345":"1345","1322":"1322","1255":"1255","about 1315":"umbes 1315","1274":"1274","18 November 1322":"18. november 1322","Llanllowell, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Llanllowell, Monmouthshire, Wales","Chewton Mendip, Somerset, England":"Chewton Mendip, Somerset, England